K-Means is an unsupervised machine learning algorithm used to group data into clusters based on similarity.
It tries to partition the dataset into K distinct clusters, where each data point belongs to the cluster with the nearest mean (centroid)

How K-Means Works (Step-by-Step)

Select a value of K (number of clusters)

Randomly initialize K centroids

Assign each data point to its nearest centroid

Recalculate centroids based on assigned points

Repeat steps 3â€“4 until centroids stop changing (convergence)


from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import numpy as np

# Sample data
data = np.array([
    [1, 2],
    [1, 4],
    [1, 0],
    [10, 2],
    [10, 4],
    [10, 0]
])

# Create model
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=2)
kmeans.fit(data)

print("Cluster Centers:", kmeans.cluster_centers_)
print("Labels:", kmeans.labels_)
